{"id":"1502.05716","submitter":"Eliahu Cohen","authors":"Yakir Aharonov, Eliahu Cohen and Daniel Rohrlich","title":"Nonlocality of the Aharonov-Bohm Effect","comments":"12 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 93, 042110 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.93.042110","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Although the Aharonov-Bohm and related effects are familiar in solid state\nand high energy physics, the nonlocality of these effects has been questioned.\nHere we show, for the first time, that the Aharonov-Bohm effect has two very\ndifferent aspects. One aspect is instantaneous and nonlocal; the other aspect,\nwhich depends on entanglement, unfolds continuously over time. While local,\ngauge-invariant variables may occasionally suffice for explaining the\ncontinuous aspect, we argue that they cannot explain the instantaneous aspect.\nThus the Aharonov-Bohm effect is, in general, nonlocal.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 19 Feb 2015 21:00:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 18 Apr 2016 17:12:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-19"}
