{"id":"1502.05876","submitter":"Gerardo Adesso","authors":"Alexander Streltsov, Uttam Singh, Himadri Shekhar Dhar, Manabendra\n  Nath Bera, Gerardo Adesso","title":"Measuring Quantum Coherence with Entanglement","comments":"5+3 pages, 1 figure. To appear in PRL","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 115, 020403 (2015)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.115.020403","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech hep-th math-ph math.MP physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum coherence is an essential ingredient in quantum information\nprocessing and plays a central role in emergent fields such as nanoscale\nthermodynamics and quantum biology. However, our understanding and quantitative\ncharacterization of coherence as an operational resource are still very\nlimited. Here we show that any degree of coherence with respect to some\nreference basis can be converted to entanglement via incoherent operations.\nThis finding allows us to define a novel general class of measures of coherence\nfor a quantum system of arbitrary dimension, in terms of the maximum bipartite\nentanglement that can be generated via incoherent operations applied to the\nsystem and an incoherent ancilla. The resulting measures are proven to be valid\ncoherence monotones satisfying all the requirements dictated by the resource\ntheory of quantum coherence. We demonstrate the usefulness of our approach by\nproving that the fidelity-based geometric measure of coherence is a full convex\ncoherence monotone, and deriving a closed formula for it on arbitrary\nsingle-qubit states. Our work provides a clear quantitative and operational\nconnection between coherence and entanglement, two landmark manifestations of\nquantum theory and both key enablers for quantum technologies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Feb 2015 14:07:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 4 Mar 2015 12:20:04 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 16 Apr 2015 